1
00:00:52,973 --> 00:00:55,487
[WHISTLING]

2
00:01:22,733 --> 00:01:26,885
Listen, snail, you'd better look out.
You're liable to be stepped on.

3
00:01:27,653 --> 00:01:29,132
Now, stay right there.

4
00:01:29,293 --> 00:01:30,521
[BIRD CAWING]

5
00:01:30,693 --> 00:01:33,366
Not so loud, Penelope,
you'll waken the master.

6
00:01:33,533 --> 00:01:35,410
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

7
00:01:35,573 --> 00:01:37,609
Penelope, who's been
teaching you to whistle?

8
00:01:37,773 --> 00:01:39,570
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

9
00:01:39,733 --> 00:01:43,646
- Hey! Shh!
- Oh, Mr. Forrester in?

10
00:01:43,813 --> 00:01:47,089
Shh! I'll take it.
He's not to be disturbed.

11
00:01:47,253 --> 00:01:50,325
- It's very important he gets it.
- Why? Have you read it?

12
00:01:50,493 --> 00:01:52,324
It's from the draft board.

13
00:01:52,493 --> 00:01:56,486
Well, Mr. Forrester is not interested,
but I'll give it to him anyway.

14
00:01:56,653 --> 00:02:00,532
Well, you'd better, or he'll take
a little jaunt to prison.

15
00:02:00,733 --> 00:02:03,088
[WHISTLING]

16
00:02:03,613 --> 00:02:07,572
STAN:
Hey, Ollie! Ollie! Hey, Ollie!

17
00:02:09,293 --> 00:02:13,366
Shh! If you must make a noise,
make it quietly.

18
00:02:16,853 --> 00:02:20,163
- What is it?
- Look. From Daniel's draft board.

19
00:02:20,333 --> 00:02:22,608
A sheer waste of postage.

20
00:02:22,773 --> 00:02:26,561
Imagine even considering a man
in Daniel Forrester's physical condition.

21
00:02:26,733 --> 00:02:28,485
I'd better give it to him anyway.

22
00:02:28,653 --> 00:02:30,723
What, and overtax his heart?
Tear it up.

23
00:02:30,893 --> 00:02:34,044
- He goes to prison if he doesn't get it.
- Nonsense.

24
00:02:34,213 --> 00:02:37,171
I suppose Dr. Schickel's examination
isn't good enough.

25
00:02:37,453 --> 00:02:40,525
Why, Daniel's allergic
to 108 different properties...

26
00:02:40,693 --> 00:02:43,924
...including candles, cucumbers
and quinces.

27
00:02:44,133 --> 00:02:46,044
Nevertheless, I'd better deliver it.

28
00:02:46,213 --> 00:02:48,852
It's the Army or prison, and if
he goes to prison...

29
00:02:50,093 --> 00:02:52,323
Penelope! You come back with that!

30
00:02:53,173 --> 00:02:54,845
MARTHA:
Good morning, Dr. Schickel.

31
00:02:55,013 --> 00:02:57,083
SCHICKEL:
Good morning. What a beautiful morning.

32
00:02:57,293 --> 00:03:00,922
The birds are singing. The sun is
shining. Everything is alive.

33
00:03:01,093 --> 00:03:03,448
- Dr. Schickel is here.
- Good morning, Daniel.

34
00:03:03,613 --> 00:03:06,332
Good morning, Dr. Schickel.
Anything new?

35
00:03:06,533 --> 00:03:08,125
Two more allergies.

36
00:03:08,293 --> 00:03:11,569
- What are they now?
- Vinegar and feathers.

37
00:03:11,733 --> 00:03:14,805
MARTHA: Oh, dear. Isn't that...?
- There, there. Don't be upset.

38
00:03:14,973 --> 00:03:17,885
Your nephew can still have his
pabulum and orange juice.

39
00:03:24,453 --> 00:03:26,648
Good morning, boys. Come in.

40
00:03:26,973 --> 00:03:31,091
Mr. Daniel, may we have
a leave of absence for a few years?

41
00:03:31,533 --> 00:03:33,489
For a few years?

42
00:03:33,653 --> 00:03:36,963
Yeah. And we're going
to prison, aren't we, Ollie?

43
00:03:37,413 --> 00:03:39,290
Well, what are you talking about?

44
00:03:39,453 --> 00:03:43,765
Well, we were going to deliver your draft
notice, when all of a sudden, Penelope...

45
00:03:43,933 --> 00:03:48,006
- Draft notice!
- My name's come up!

46
00:03:48,373 --> 00:03:53,208
- Do you think I have a chance, doctor?
- As much as a snowball in an incubator.

47
00:03:53,373 --> 00:03:56,046
MARTHA: Thank heavens!
AGATHA: Why, it's perfectly ridiculous.

48
00:03:56,213 --> 00:03:58,966
- He couldn't join the woodcraft boys.
- Eureka!

49
00:03:59,133 --> 00:04:01,010
Penelope, you naughty girl.

50
00:04:01,173 --> 00:04:02,845
It's my notice, all right.

51
00:04:03,013 --> 00:04:05,811
- Yeah, and by airmail.
SCHICKEL: Get that bird out of here!

52
00:04:05,973 --> 00:04:08,885
Get away, get away!

53
00:04:09,053 --> 00:04:10,725
He's allergic to feathers.

54
00:04:10,893 --> 00:04:14,568
- I'm to appear for induction tomorrow.
- Oh, there must be some mistake.

55
00:04:14,733 --> 00:04:16,212
Maybe they'll take me.

56
00:04:16,373 --> 00:04:18,807
I will just send them
a few of your x-rays.

57
00:04:18,973 --> 00:04:21,692
But it says I must appear personally,
and I'm going.

58
00:04:24,413 --> 00:04:25,528
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

59
00:04:32,173 --> 00:04:33,526
Good morning, everyone.

60
00:04:33,693 --> 00:04:35,843
- Good morning, Ollie.
- Not you.

61
00:04:36,013 --> 00:04:38,652
If that guy makes it,
my Aunt Minnie will join up.

62
00:04:38,813 --> 00:04:41,725
There you are, sir.
Daniel Forrester IV.

63
00:04:41,893 --> 00:04:44,453
- Sit down, please.
- Thank you. Over here, Daniel.

64
00:04:44,613 --> 00:04:47,332
SCHICKEL: Gently, gently!
- Yes, doctor.

65
00:04:50,133 --> 00:04:51,532
Put that match out, quick!

66
00:04:51,693 --> 00:04:56,244
- I don't see a "No Smoking" sign.
- He's allergic to sulfur.

67
00:04:58,973 --> 00:05:00,884
- Next man.
MAN: Frank Dombrowski.

68
00:05:01,053 --> 00:05:03,613
FRANK: Yes, sir.
- Dombrowski? In here.

69
00:05:03,773 --> 00:05:06,492
Pardon me, captain,
I'm Dr. Hugo Schickel.

70
00:05:06,653 --> 00:05:11,773
Through some stupid mistake, my patient
has been ordered here for examination.

71
00:05:11,933 --> 00:05:16,245
For 15 years I have struggled
to keep this pitiful boy alive.

72
00:05:16,413 --> 00:05:21,612
One look at this and you can readily see
he's a doomed man.

73
00:05:21,773 --> 00:05:25,049
Army regulations require
more than one look, Dr. Schickel.

74
00:05:25,373 --> 00:05:27,933
If you'll just step in there,
young man.

75
00:05:28,693 --> 00:05:32,481
I'm sorry, doctor. Our examinations
are conducted by Army men only.

76
00:05:32,653 --> 00:05:34,371
You'll excuse us.

77
00:05:34,533 --> 00:05:36,842
SCHICKEL:
Army doctors.

78
00:05:37,013 --> 00:05:39,652
Don't let him out of your sight.

79
00:05:47,013 --> 00:05:49,322
- Snake bite?
- I'm testing his blood pressure.

80
00:05:49,493 --> 00:05:51,643
Outside, please.

81
00:05:52,013 --> 00:05:55,449
You're wasting your time.
You won't find any blood.

82
00:05:55,613 --> 00:05:56,841
You certainly won't.

83
00:05:57,013 --> 00:06:00,449
For his birthday, we were gonna
give him a blood transfusion.

84
00:06:00,613 --> 00:06:02,649
DOCTOR:
Please!

85
00:06:03,413 --> 00:06:05,529
- How old are you?
- Twenty-three.

86
00:06:05,693 --> 00:06:08,969
And already a doddering old man.

87
00:06:09,133 --> 00:06:12,682
Take a look at his ribs.
You can use them for a washboard.

88
00:06:12,853 --> 00:06:15,048
Your blood pressure
is perfectly normal.

89
00:06:15,213 --> 00:06:16,646
I can't believe it.

90
00:06:16,813 --> 00:06:20,601
If you'll tap him, you'll find
that his blood is pure sugar.

91
00:06:20,773 --> 00:06:23,048
Dr. Schickel says
he's a walking maple tree.

92
00:06:23,213 --> 00:06:24,441
[WHISTLING]

93
00:06:24,613 --> 00:06:29,403
You hear that? His blood is so thin
you can hear it flowing through his veins.

94
00:06:31,373 --> 00:06:35,002
- Must be the whistle he swallowed.
- Uh-uh. That's me.

95
00:06:35,173 --> 00:06:37,892
- Well, keep quiet!
- What's the verdict, doctor?

96
00:06:38,053 --> 00:06:40,283
- Perfect.
- Is there anything wrong with me?

97
00:06:40,453 --> 00:06:42,489
Nothing a year in the Army won't cure.

98
00:06:42,693 --> 00:06:45,161
You mean he's passed the examination?

99
00:06:45,373 --> 00:06:48,046
One hundred percent.

100
00:06:48,973 --> 00:06:49,962
[GLASS SHATTERING]

101
00:06:50,133 --> 00:06:51,327
[THUD]

102
00:06:56,973 --> 00:07:01,046
Sarge, the cook says if the draftees
aren't in by 7, they don't get breakfast.

103
00:07:01,213 --> 00:07:04,250
Well, tell him to keep his pores closed.
The train's late.

104
00:07:10,613 --> 00:07:13,685
MAN 1:
Lafayette, here we are!

105
00:07:14,213 --> 00:07:16,522
Lafayette, we are here!

106
00:07:23,493 --> 00:07:27,281
- Is that all the men?
- There are a couple more inside.

107
00:07:29,133 --> 00:07:30,964
[LAUGHING]

108
00:07:34,893 --> 00:07:37,885
- You think you're on a clambake?
- We didn't hear a bugle.

109
00:07:38,093 --> 00:07:41,722
- There wasn't any bugle.
- So that's why we didn't hear it.

110
00:07:41,893 --> 00:07:44,202
Pipe down.
Now, we've only got till 7.

111
00:07:44,373 --> 00:07:46,933
Those who want breakfast,
take it on the double.

112
00:07:47,133 --> 00:07:50,284
Captain, Mr. Forrester
is not very strong.

113
00:07:50,453 --> 00:07:53,092
We enlisted to see
that he got proper care.

114
00:07:53,333 --> 00:07:54,607
Oh, I see.

115
00:07:54,813 --> 00:07:57,725
If you'll show us to his suite,
we'll serve him there.

116
00:07:57,893 --> 00:08:02,409
I'm sorry. We aimed to have that left
wing finished by the time you got here.

117
00:08:02,573 --> 00:08:05,212
I'll move the general
out of his quarters tomorrow.

118
00:08:05,413 --> 00:08:09,088
Well, under those circumstances,
we'll wait.

119
00:08:09,613 --> 00:08:13,367
If you don't wanna eat, you're
coming along anyway for the exercise.

120
00:08:13,533 --> 00:08:16,172
MAN 2: I never eat this late.
MAN 3: I could eat this horse.

121
00:08:16,333 --> 00:08:18,130
MAN 4:
I could go for some more shuteye.

122
00:08:18,613 --> 00:08:20,683
MAN 5:
Hey, where's the café?

123
00:08:21,253 --> 00:08:23,369
Why, Penelope!
What are you doing here?

124
00:08:23,533 --> 00:08:25,569
Well, what a small world.

125
00:08:25,773 --> 00:08:29,846
- What's the idea of that bird?
- Why, Stan and Penelope are inseparable.

126
00:08:30,013 --> 00:08:31,685
That vulture ain't camping here.

127
00:08:31,853 --> 00:08:34,572
Tell her to scram or I call out
the anti-aircraft.

128
00:08:34,773 --> 00:08:37,731
Did you hear what he said?
You'd better fly on home.

129
00:08:37,893 --> 00:08:40,612
Go on, Penelope, go on.

130
00:08:40,813 --> 00:08:44,283
It's 1500 miles,
as the crow flies.

131
00:08:44,453 --> 00:08:48,162
Yeah. And turn to your left at St. Louis.

132
00:08:48,573 --> 00:08:52,885
- Goodbye.
- All right, men, follow me, on the double.

133
00:08:53,093 --> 00:08:55,163
[CHATTER]

134
00:09:04,133 --> 00:09:05,407
STAN:
Bread and butter.

135
00:09:49,173 --> 00:09:51,403
HIPPO:
Detail halt!

136
00:09:51,773 --> 00:09:53,411
[PANTING]

137
00:09:55,733 --> 00:09:57,007
At ease!

138
00:10:00,493 --> 00:10:04,645
All right, men. Leave your luggage here.
Breakfast on the double.

139
00:10:11,773 --> 00:10:14,082
[KITCHEN CLATTER]

140
00:10:21,733 --> 00:10:23,963
Thank you, Ollie.

141
00:10:26,653 --> 00:10:29,486
Get to the end of the line, blimp!

142
00:10:29,733 --> 00:10:32,884
How do you like that guy,
trying to ease in there?

143
00:10:33,253 --> 00:10:35,244
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

144
00:10:54,853 --> 00:10:56,650
MAN 1:
Hey, chef.

145
00:11:03,173 --> 00:11:04,447
MAN 2:
Hey, chef.

146
00:11:04,613 --> 00:11:07,173
All right. Take it easy.
I've only got two hands.

147
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:10,245
MAN 3: Plenty for everybody, boys.
Take your time.

148
00:11:43,533 --> 00:11:45,763
OLLIE:
Get some butter.

149
00:12:04,573 --> 00:12:07,326
- Sanka?
- You're welcome.

150
00:12:10,253 --> 00:12:12,403
- Here we are.
- Well done, Stanley.

151
00:12:12,573 --> 00:12:14,325
Thank you, Ollie.

152
00:12:16,733 --> 00:12:19,247
Hey, look. Hey, listen.

153
00:12:19,413 --> 00:12:22,564
- You can't eat eggs.
- You know you're allergic to albumen.

154
00:12:22,733 --> 00:12:24,485
I'm starved, and I'm going to eat.

155
00:12:24,653 --> 00:12:27,042
What did Dr. Schickel
say about pumpernickel?

156
00:12:27,213 --> 00:12:29,727
What did the Army doctor
say about Schickel?

157
00:12:29,893 --> 00:12:33,647
Here, Daniel. There's a seven-course
dinner in one of these teeny pills.

158
00:12:33,813 --> 00:12:36,043
In fact, a concentrated banquet.

159
00:12:36,213 --> 00:12:40,172
- Does it have bacon and eggs in it?
- No, but it has essence of guinea fowl.

160
00:12:40,333 --> 00:12:43,086
And spirits of spinach.
Go on, it's good for you.

161
00:12:43,253 --> 00:12:46,882
No, boys, I'm going to eat food.

162
00:12:47,053 --> 00:12:48,884
Even if it kills me.

163
00:12:49,053 --> 00:12:50,452
It's suicide.

164
00:12:50,653 --> 00:12:54,362
Now, look, fellas, it was swell of you
to join the Army to be with me.

165
00:12:54,533 --> 00:12:57,809
But you have enough to do
serving Uncle Sam without serving me.

166
00:12:59,053 --> 00:13:01,408
We can take care of both of you.

167
00:13:01,573 --> 00:13:05,612
Well, in the meantime, you'd better
take care of your own breakfast. Look.

168
00:13:07,013 --> 00:13:09,481
Pardon me. Haven't you gentlemen
made a mistake?

169
00:13:09,653 --> 00:13:12,963
- Those are our eggs.
- Yeah? When did you lay them?

170
00:13:13,133 --> 00:13:16,409
- I laid them on the tray a minute ago.
- Yeah.

171
00:13:16,573 --> 00:13:19,087
- Did you hear anyone cackle?
- Not me.

172
00:13:19,253 --> 00:13:22,563
We don't want to have any trouble,
but really, we are hungry.

173
00:13:22,733 --> 00:13:24,610
We haven't eaten for three days.

174
00:13:24,773 --> 00:13:26,729
Yesterday, today and tomorrow.

175
00:13:26,893 --> 00:13:29,885
An army travels on its stomach,
you know.

176
00:13:30,053 --> 00:13:33,489
What are you beefing about?
You got enough to make China and back.

177
00:13:33,653 --> 00:13:35,484
Now, get going.

178
00:13:35,853 --> 00:13:38,606
- Come on.
- Well, we don't know the way to China.

179
00:13:38,773 --> 00:13:40,126
How ca...?

180
00:13:41,293 --> 00:13:43,011
Boy, am I hungry.

181
00:13:43,173 --> 00:13:45,892
There's a seven-course dinner
in one of these pills.

182
00:13:46,053 --> 00:13:48,806
- That ought to hold you till lunch.
HIPPO: All right, men.

183
00:13:49,013 --> 00:13:51,732
Going to the Reception Center.
We've got 20 minutes.

184
00:13:51,933 --> 00:13:53,889
So let's get going. On the double.

185
00:14:04,133 --> 00:14:05,407
- Ollie.
- What?

186
00:14:05,573 --> 00:14:08,133
- I'm still hungry.
- Glutton!

187
00:14:08,293 --> 00:14:11,251
HIPPO:
I said, on the double! Come on!

188
00:14:32,573 --> 00:14:35,371
- Good morning, sergeant.
- Good morning, colonel.

189
00:14:35,533 --> 00:14:37,603
A likely looking bunch
of men, sergeant.

190
00:14:37,773 --> 00:14:39,445
Thank you, sir.

191
00:14:52,093 --> 00:14:55,972
- I guess I spoke too soon.
- Why, yes, sir.

192
00:15:01,053 --> 00:15:03,123
Is this uniform the best they could do?

193
00:15:03,333 --> 00:15:06,211
Oh, I don't mind.
The man said I'd grow into it.

194
00:15:06,373 --> 00:15:08,762
Dad, would you mind
taking a picture of us?

195
00:15:08,933 --> 00:15:12,005
We wanna show the folks
back home how we look.

196
00:15:12,533 --> 00:15:14,410
- Why, certainly.
- Thank you.

197
00:15:14,573 --> 00:15:17,770
- Not too close.
- Yes, get back just a little.

198
00:15:22,573 --> 00:15:25,212
Give it a little dignity.

199
00:15:26,093 --> 00:15:29,085
COLONEL: Ready?
- Shoot, Pop!

200
00:15:30,453 --> 00:15:33,172
- Thanks.
- lf they turn out good, we'll give you one.

201
00:15:33,333 --> 00:15:35,893
- Good.
- How long you been in the Army?

202
00:15:36,333 --> 00:15:39,609
- Thirty-two years.
- You must be a sergeant.

203
00:15:39,773 --> 00:15:42,003
- No.
- Surely a corporal.

204
00:15:42,613 --> 00:15:45,127
COLONEL:
I'm afraid I'm not that lucky.

205
00:15:45,413 --> 00:15:49,929
Thirty-two years in the Army
and not even a corporal?

206
00:15:50,773 --> 00:15:54,971
Stan, at last I've met somebody
that's dumber than you.

207
00:15:56,333 --> 00:15:58,449
Attention!

208
00:15:58,893 --> 00:16:02,408
- Carry on, sergeant.
- Penelope, you mustn't hang around here.

209
00:16:02,613 --> 00:16:04,092
What is this, a circus?

210
00:16:04,253 --> 00:16:07,643
- Get rid of that bird immediately.
- Yes, sir.

211
00:16:11,733 --> 00:16:14,725
What did I ever do to deserve
a couple of yaps like you?

212
00:16:14,933 --> 00:16:17,163
- You were good to your mother?
HIPPO: Pipe down.

213
00:16:17,333 --> 00:16:18,322
Yes, sir.

214
00:16:18,493 --> 00:16:21,132
At 10:00 you're all going over
for an IQ test.

215
00:16:21,293 --> 00:16:24,444
According to your answers,
you'll be classified in a job.

216
00:16:24,613 --> 00:16:26,808
Swell. We're good at quizzes,
aren't we?

217
00:16:26,973 --> 00:16:29,362
Maybe they'll put me in
the Intelligence Corps.

218
00:16:30,013 --> 00:16:33,403
Brother, you're with him, right now.

219
00:16:50,213 --> 00:16:52,124
Where can I get some films developed?

220
00:16:52,293 --> 00:16:55,330
- Hammonds' Photo Shop, over there.
- Thanks.

221
00:17:06,093 --> 00:17:08,004
- Oh, hello, sergeant.
- Hi.

222
00:17:08,173 --> 00:17:10,403
We seem to be bumping
into each other today.

223
00:17:10,573 --> 00:17:11,972
You'll get used to that.

224
00:17:12,133 --> 00:17:14,852
Where's the clerk?
I wanna have some films developed.

225
00:17:15,013 --> 00:17:18,050
In a hurry? Drop them in the box,
leave your name on them.

226
00:17:18,213 --> 00:17:19,851
My camera's jammed here.

227
00:17:20,013 --> 00:17:22,163
Oh, yeah? Here, I'll open it for you.

228
00:17:22,333 --> 00:17:24,801
Don't... Not in the light.
You'll spoil the film.

229
00:17:24,973 --> 00:17:26,645
- Well, I'm an old...
GINGER: Hippo.

230
00:17:27,493 --> 00:17:29,882
- Hello. Be with you in a moment.
DANIEL: I can wait.

231
00:17:30,053 --> 00:17:32,442
I can't find your pictures.
You in a hurry?

232
00:17:32,613 --> 00:17:34,649
I can help you.
I got eyes like an owl.

233
00:17:34,813 --> 00:17:36,610
Yes, and hands like an octopus.

234
00:17:36,773 --> 00:17:40,607
- I'll get along better if you stay outside.
- Ginger, you got me all wrong.

235
00:17:40,773 --> 00:17:43,412
Remember, out of bounds.

236
00:17:43,613 --> 00:17:46,730
- Ain't she the essence of peppermint?
- She's very nice.

237
00:17:46,893 --> 00:17:50,090
Very nice? She's the best filly
that ever hit the cavalry.

238
00:17:50,253 --> 00:17:54,246
- Well, perhaps if I knew her better...
- Forget it. You won't have time to.

239
00:17:54,413 --> 00:17:56,404
I found them in with Colonel Higgins'.

240
00:17:56,573 --> 00:17:58,643
HIPPO:
It's a good thing he didn't see them.

241
00:17:58,813 --> 00:18:01,202
They're snaps of me taking jumps
on his horse.

242
00:18:01,373 --> 00:18:02,965
I'm sorry to keep you waiting.

243
00:18:03,133 --> 00:18:05,283
That's okay.
Mind if I use your darkroom?

244
00:18:05,493 --> 00:18:08,246
The film's jammed in my camera.

245
00:18:08,613 --> 00:18:10,171
Well, go ahead.

246
00:18:11,613 --> 00:18:14,173
- And don't scratch the negative.
- I hope not.

247
00:18:14,333 --> 00:18:17,769
- They're my first pictures at camp.
- Maybe I better do it for you.

248
00:18:17,933 --> 00:18:21,642
- I don't wanna put you to any trouble.
- Well, that's what I'm here for.

249
00:18:22,533 --> 00:18:24,842
That don't add up.

250
00:18:25,053 --> 00:18:27,169
Now, you turn that little key.

251
00:18:28,453 --> 00:18:32,128
- It's really jammed, all right.
- Now, slip your hand under mine.

252
00:18:32,413 --> 00:18:34,608
And when I squeeze,
you pull the catch.

253
00:18:34,773 --> 00:18:37,241
DANIEL: All right, I'm ready.
GINGER: There.

254
00:18:37,413 --> 00:18:39,688
DANIEL: Shall I unroll it?
- Why not develop it?

255
00:18:39,853 --> 00:18:42,447
- Will it take long?
- Just a few minutes.

256
00:18:44,853 --> 00:18:47,083
You haven't been in the Army long,
have you?

257
00:18:47,253 --> 00:18:48,732
How can you tell?

258
00:18:48,893 --> 00:18:51,282
I don't know. You looked shy
when you came in.

259
00:18:51,453 --> 00:18:54,172
Well, I was sort of surprised
to see a girl here.

260
00:18:54,373 --> 00:18:56,762
Especially such a pretty one.

261
00:18:57,293 --> 00:18:59,932
- Now you're sounding like a trooper.
- Is that good?

262
00:19:00,093 --> 00:19:02,129
Well, not in the darkroom.

263
00:19:04,253 --> 00:19:05,527
What's that, a balloon?

264
00:19:05,693 --> 00:19:07,206
No, that's my friend Oliver.

265
00:19:07,373 --> 00:19:10,171
- What's that next to him?
- That's the other one, Stan.

266
00:19:10,333 --> 00:19:12,563
They used to work for me.
Now we're buddies.

267
00:19:12,733 --> 00:19:14,724
Has Ripley seen them?

268
00:19:14,933 --> 00:19:16,730
[LAUGHING]

269
00:19:23,733 --> 00:19:25,689
I'm sorry,
was there something else?

270
00:19:25,853 --> 00:19:27,684
You wanna collect for the pictures?

271
00:19:27,853 --> 00:19:30,651
- Are you gonna pay cash this time?
- Yeah, how much?

272
00:19:30,813 --> 00:19:33,202
- Dollar-twenty.
DANIEL: When will mine be finished?

273
00:19:33,373 --> 00:19:34,806
- Tomorrow night.
- I'll be in.

274
00:19:34,973 --> 00:19:37,771
- What's your name?
- I'll bring them. He's in my troop.

275
00:19:37,933 --> 00:19:39,844
Don't bother.
I can pick them up.

276
00:19:40,013 --> 00:19:42,811
No bother at all. Always glad
to do a favor for a pal.

277
00:19:42,973 --> 00:19:44,486
- See you later.
- Goodbye.

278
00:19:44,693 --> 00:19:48,003
Well, say, sergeant.
You're a nice fella.

279
00:19:48,173 --> 00:19:52,132
Next time you want pictures developed,
drop them in that box and evacuate.

280
00:19:52,293 --> 00:19:54,204
- But...
- The darkroom's out of bounds.

281
00:19:54,373 --> 00:19:57,365
Wanna learn how to develop?
Transfer to the Signal Corps.

282
00:19:57,533 --> 00:19:59,364
- But my camera was jammed.
- Oh, yeah?

283
00:19:59,533 --> 00:20:01,842
The next time I'm gonna jam that camera
right down...

284
00:20:02,013 --> 00:20:03,048
[BUGLE PLAYING]

285
00:20:03,213 --> 00:20:05,249
That's assembly. Now, get going.

286
00:20:05,413 --> 00:20:08,689
In the meantime, I'm gonna pick out
a nice, cush job for you.

287
00:20:08,853 --> 00:20:11,162
Well, thank you, sergeant.

288
00:20:13,813 --> 00:20:16,452
MAN 1: Come on, cowboy!
MAN 2: Hang on to the bronc!

289
00:20:16,653 --> 00:20:18,405
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

290
00:20:29,253 --> 00:20:30,652
[GASPING]

291
00:20:31,933 --> 00:20:35,130
- They don't even give him a parachute.
- Or a pillow.

292
00:20:38,293 --> 00:20:40,682
There, how do you like that
for riding, Ginger?

293
00:20:40,853 --> 00:20:45,688
- That's Corporal Peters, isn't it?
- One of the saltiest guys in the troop.

294
00:20:47,173 --> 00:20:50,370
Why, he couldn't ride a rocking horse
when he first came here.

295
00:20:50,533 --> 00:20:52,603
I taught him everything he knows.

296
00:20:56,253 --> 00:20:58,130
Is that so?

297
00:20:58,293 --> 00:21:00,682
How do you like that?

298
00:21:03,373 --> 00:21:04,806
Now, listen, men.

299
00:21:04,973 --> 00:21:09,364
If you think we've put on this rodeo
just to entertain you guys, you're wrong.

300
00:21:09,533 --> 00:21:13,287
After you get your training,
some of you'll do a hitch in this corral.

301
00:21:13,493 --> 00:21:16,053
Now, the Army needs riders
to bust remounts.

302
00:21:16,253 --> 00:21:19,325
Any of you that have had
horse experience, we can use you.

303
00:21:19,493 --> 00:21:22,690
I been tangling with broncs
since I was knee-high to a coyote.

304
00:21:22,893 --> 00:21:24,246
Good.

305
00:21:30,573 --> 00:21:32,291
How about you, Mr. Moneybags?

306
00:21:32,493 --> 00:21:35,166
Well, I did some riding
on our estate in Vermont.

307
00:21:35,373 --> 00:21:37,568
But then he was only a little twerp.

308
00:21:37,733 --> 00:21:40,008
That was long before he was stricken.

309
00:21:40,213 --> 00:21:42,408
I see you got your alibi all set up.

310
00:21:42,573 --> 00:21:44,768
You can cough up that silver spoon now.

311
00:21:44,933 --> 00:21:47,811
Because in the Army,
we all start from scratch.

312
00:21:50,133 --> 00:21:52,772
Just a minute, sergeant.
I'll give it a try.

313
00:21:52,973 --> 00:21:56,363
Daniel. Daniel, don't say that.

314
00:21:56,573 --> 00:21:58,962
He couldn't be trusted
on a merry-go-round.

315
00:21:59,133 --> 00:22:01,727
STAN:
It's suicide, sergeant.

316
00:22:01,893 --> 00:22:04,487
- What do you say, soldier?
- Get a horse ready.

317
00:22:04,653 --> 00:22:08,566
Okay. Hey, Murph, throw a
saddle on that new one, 806.

318
00:22:08,733 --> 00:22:10,485
BOTH: Say, Daniel...
- Come back here.

319
00:22:10,653 --> 00:22:12,689
Agatha and Martha
won't forgive us.

320
00:22:12,853 --> 00:22:14,332
STAN:
Listen.

321
00:22:14,533 --> 00:22:16,763
[HORSE WHINNYING]

322
00:22:27,413 --> 00:22:29,529
Good luck, soldier.

323
00:22:30,893 --> 00:22:33,726
Don't you know that you're allergic
to horses too?

324
00:22:33,893 --> 00:22:35,167
DANIEL:
Let him go.

325
00:22:36,053 --> 00:22:37,725
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

326
00:22:39,373 --> 00:22:40,362
BOTH:
Daniel!

327
00:22:40,533 --> 00:22:42,489
- Get off there. It's a wild horse.
- Oh! Oh!

328
00:22:46,773 --> 00:22:48,684
Is he still on the horse?

329
00:22:48,853 --> 00:22:50,445
Look!

330
00:22:50,813 --> 00:22:51,928
Oh!

331
00:22:52,093 --> 00:22:53,367
- Stop!
MAN 3: Hang on!

332
00:22:53,533 --> 00:22:55,603
Attaboy!

333
00:22:58,213 --> 00:23:01,683
- He's doing all right.
- Why, sure.

334
00:23:02,973 --> 00:23:05,168
MAN 4:
Hang on to him, boy.

335
00:23:06,533 --> 00:23:07,852
What a rider!

336
00:23:08,013 --> 00:23:10,686
Yeah, but he ain't riding regulation.

337
00:23:10,853 --> 00:23:13,970
Look at that hump on his back.
It looks like a knapsack.

338
00:23:15,173 --> 00:23:17,846
Look at the way he's hanging on
to that saddle.

339
00:23:18,453 --> 00:23:20,330
That's what I call disgusting.

340
00:23:20,853 --> 00:23:23,526
Why don't you show him how, sergeant.

341
00:23:24,253 --> 00:23:27,484
All right, I will. Pick him up.

342
00:23:32,493 --> 00:23:35,246
Hey, you're all nerve and no talent.

343
00:23:35,573 --> 00:23:39,805
I'll show you how to ride regulation.
Get a load of this technique.

344
00:23:44,493 --> 00:23:46,165
Let her go!

345
00:23:50,893 --> 00:23:52,042
[LAUGHING]

346
00:23:58,213 --> 00:24:01,205
Why didn't you guys wait
till I was ready?

347
00:24:11,573 --> 00:24:13,211
[PANTING]

348
00:24:13,373 --> 00:24:14,692
[SIGHING]

349
00:24:19,653 --> 00:24:22,690
You thought it was funny
when the horse threw the sergeant.

350
00:24:22,853 --> 00:24:25,128
Well, after all,
I only smiled out loud.

351
00:24:25,293 --> 00:24:28,490
Yeah. You smiled so loud
that he had us tow these nags...

352
00:24:28,653 --> 00:24:32,282
...five miles uphill just to exercise them.

353
00:24:32,453 --> 00:24:34,683
Well, it'll do them good.

354
00:24:34,853 --> 00:24:37,970
Well, I'm going to take
a little nap right here.

355
00:24:38,133 --> 00:24:40,363
I guess the Army
wouldn't miss a little nap.

356
00:24:40,533 --> 00:24:44,412
- But we'd better not oversleep.
- We'll take turns. Ten minutes each.

357
00:24:44,573 --> 00:24:45,892
That's a good idea.

358
00:24:46,453 --> 00:24:48,489
Oh, boy.

359
00:24:49,013 --> 00:24:51,129
Oh, this is...

360
00:24:54,573 --> 00:24:56,723
Selfish.

361
00:25:03,893 --> 00:25:05,565
[GUNS FIRING]

362
00:25:08,173 --> 00:25:11,768
- What's that?
- Would they declare war without us?

363
00:25:11,933 --> 00:25:13,082
The horses!

364
00:25:13,253 --> 00:25:16,723
- What'll the sergeant say?
- We'd better get back to camp.

365
00:25:25,453 --> 00:25:26,806
Cease firing!

366
00:25:28,693 --> 00:25:29,842
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

367
00:25:32,173 --> 00:25:34,368
MAN:
Hits, 92 percent.

368
00:25:35,973 --> 00:25:37,964
Take it through again, Smitty.

369
00:25:39,173 --> 00:25:42,961
[OLLIE GRUNTING AND GROANING]

370
00:25:46,733 --> 00:25:50,248
- Look.
- It's only a dead dud.

371
00:25:51,093 --> 00:25:54,085
Don't throw it away.
We'll keep it as a souvenir.

372
00:25:54,253 --> 00:25:57,131
- All right.
- Hey, look.

373
00:26:00,453 --> 00:26:04,332
- Let's steal a ride back to camp.
- Okay.

374
00:26:19,493 --> 00:26:21,245
Strange-looking vehicle, isn't it?

375
00:26:21,413 --> 00:26:24,644
Yeah, it looks like one of those
election-campaign wagons.

376
00:26:24,813 --> 00:26:27,008
Maybe they're electing a new general.

377
00:26:27,173 --> 00:26:32,008
Well, if the sergeant's running,
I'm not so sure if I'd vote for him or not.

378
00:26:32,173 --> 00:26:34,687
That goes double.

379
00:26:35,933 --> 00:26:37,924
Commence firing.

380
00:26:38,093 --> 00:26:39,242
[GUNS FIRING]

381
00:26:47,333 --> 00:26:50,245
- What's that?
- Sounds like an Oregon woodpecker.

382
00:26:50,413 --> 00:26:53,644
No. An Oregon woodpecker
makes a much softer sound.

383
00:26:53,813 --> 00:26:57,123
That's like the Tennessee woodpecker
that thrives on hickory.

384
00:26:57,293 --> 00:26:58,806
It goes something like this:

385
00:26:58,973 --> 00:27:00,326
[IMITATING WOODPECKER]

386
00:27:04,493 --> 00:27:06,643
Is it that loud?

387
00:27:06,973 --> 00:27:08,691
Did I hear shooting?

388
00:27:08,853 --> 00:27:11,162
No, that was you
imitating a woodpecker.

389
00:27:11,333 --> 00:27:14,086
And very good too.

390
00:27:18,373 --> 00:27:20,933
Did you notice these holes before?

391
00:27:21,093 --> 00:27:23,163
I don't remember.

392
00:27:27,253 --> 00:27:29,289
We're at war!
The enemy's firing on us.

393
00:27:29,453 --> 00:27:31,842
- I can't hear you. The noise.
- Machine guns.

394
00:27:32,013 --> 00:27:35,449
- What?
- Get down. Do you wanna be killed?

395
00:27:36,213 --> 00:27:37,726
[GUNS FIRING]

396
00:27:46,733 --> 00:27:48,451
Pull in your tummy!

397
00:27:50,853 --> 00:27:52,366
Stop shooting!

398
00:27:52,533 --> 00:27:54,012
We'll surrender!

399
00:27:58,133 --> 00:28:00,408
Cease firing.

400
00:28:01,253 --> 00:28:02,447
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

401
00:28:04,013 --> 00:28:08,564
- We'd better report this.
- We'd better get out of here.

402
00:28:09,813 --> 00:28:11,929
Let's go!

403
00:28:16,253 --> 00:28:17,732
Ah!

404
00:28:19,373 --> 00:28:21,933
Well, I'm a pigeon-toed prairie dog!

405
00:28:24,813 --> 00:28:26,451
DANIEL:
Did you boys get lost?

406
00:28:26,613 --> 00:28:29,286
- What an experience we have had.
- We sure have.

407
00:28:29,453 --> 00:28:31,683
DANIEL: What now?
- We're at war.

408
00:28:31,853 --> 00:28:35,448
- What are you talking about?
- We were attacked by machine guns.

409
00:28:35,613 --> 00:28:37,410
They weren't woodpeckers either.

410
00:28:37,773 --> 00:28:40,003
You boys better watch your diet.

411
00:28:40,613 --> 00:28:43,173
There you are. I told you
he wouldn't believe us.

412
00:28:43,333 --> 00:28:45,608
- Look.
- Where'd you get that?

413
00:28:45,813 --> 00:28:47,212
On the battlefield.

414
00:28:47,373 --> 00:28:50,809
We're gonna make a bud vase
for Aunt Agatha and Martha.

415
00:28:51,013 --> 00:28:52,287
- How?
- Well, like this:

416
00:28:52,453 --> 00:28:55,047
DANIEL: Look out!
- It's all right. It's only a dud dead.

417
00:28:55,213 --> 00:28:57,852
- A dead dud.
- See? It's all tarnished.

418
00:28:58,013 --> 00:29:00,846
Won't that make a pretty souvenir
after it's polished?

419
00:29:01,053 --> 00:29:03,089
Look, it's full of powder.

420
00:29:03,893 --> 00:29:06,487
Hey! That's Private Meeley's tobacco!

421
00:29:06,693 --> 00:29:09,446
So it is. I'll take it outside and sift it.

422
00:29:09,613 --> 00:29:11,649
Yeah, we'll sift it.

423
00:29:11,813 --> 00:29:13,724
Here you are!

424
00:29:14,453 --> 00:29:17,251
The horses came in alone and sweating.
Where you been?

425
00:29:17,413 --> 00:29:19,290
- Didn't they tell you?
- Who?

426
00:29:19,453 --> 00:29:20,806
The horses. No, I mean...

427
00:29:20,973 --> 00:29:23,407
- Funny man, huh?
- No, we've got news for you.

428
00:29:23,573 --> 00:29:24,892
- Haven't we, Ollie?
- Yeah.

429
00:29:25,053 --> 00:29:27,851
- Yeah? Spill it.
- We're at war.

430
00:29:28,013 --> 00:29:30,652
- Look.
- They shot them off.

431
00:29:30,853 --> 00:29:33,208
Don't give me that malarkey.

432
00:29:33,373 --> 00:29:35,682
Why, this tent looks like a flophouse.

433
00:29:35,853 --> 00:29:37,491
Do you guys have pillow fights?

434
00:29:37,653 --> 00:29:40,008
No, sir. We're too tired for that.

435
00:29:40,173 --> 00:29:42,482
We're having an inspection
by General Taylor.

436
00:29:42,693 --> 00:29:44,490
- Who's that?
- Never mind.

437
00:29:44,653 --> 00:29:47,042
Police up this tent
and get into dress O.D.'s.

438
00:29:47,213 --> 00:29:48,692
Yes, sir.

439
00:29:48,933 --> 00:29:51,493
That goes for you too, Mr. Pot o' Gold.

440
00:29:51,653 --> 00:29:53,484
Will I have time to wash up?

441
00:29:53,653 --> 00:29:56,247
All right, but make it snappy.

442
00:29:58,933 --> 00:30:00,207
Come on, get with it.

443
00:30:00,373 --> 00:30:02,682
- On the double?
- Yes.

444
00:30:06,013 --> 00:30:08,652
- Make up this cot, regulation.
- Yes, sir.

445
00:30:08,813 --> 00:30:11,532
- And this one too.
- Yes, sir.

446
00:30:23,173 --> 00:30:24,208
[GASPS]

447
00:30:24,373 --> 00:30:26,648
- Just a minute...
- None of your lip, rookie.

448
00:30:26,813 --> 00:30:28,644
Fold that blanket
like I showed you.

449
00:30:28,813 --> 00:30:31,885
- Sir, that's not...
- You gonna tell me how to make a bed?

450
00:30:32,053 --> 00:30:35,443
- No, but...
- And there's no "buts" in the Army.

451
00:30:41,253 --> 00:30:45,007
What are you two yaps doing,
playing games?

452
00:30:45,213 --> 00:30:48,649
- We were only trying to tell you...
- You ain't telling me anything.

453
00:30:48,813 --> 00:30:51,373
Stop arguing. If you spoil
Troop D's record...

454
00:30:51,533 --> 00:30:54,570
...I'll run you through a meat-grinder.
Rattle your hocks.

455
00:30:55,013 --> 00:30:58,323
- But you won't listen.
- Now, get this.

456
00:31:01,053 --> 00:31:04,568
I'm the big noise around here.
And you guys do the listening, see?

457
00:31:04,733 --> 00:31:06,530
Give me a match.

458
00:31:12,573 --> 00:31:15,007
And you yaps be ready.

459
00:31:18,173 --> 00:31:20,403
The sergeant is certainly
a headstrong man.

460
00:31:20,573 --> 00:31:22,643
You're right. He doesn't appreciate
real friends.

461
00:31:22,813 --> 00:31:24,041
[EXPLOSION]

462
00:31:24,213 --> 00:31:26,602
- What was that?
- I heard something too.

463
00:31:26,773 --> 00:31:29,412
Possibly a woodpecker.

464
00:31:35,333 --> 00:31:37,449
Look. They've assigned us a porter.

465
00:31:37,613 --> 00:31:41,526
You may start over here, my good man,
and you may have Thursdays off.

466
00:31:41,733 --> 00:31:43,052
Twice a week.

467
00:31:43,253 --> 00:31:45,687
Listen, you jugheads!

468
00:31:45,853 --> 00:31:47,491
It sounds like Sergeant Hippo.

469
00:31:47,653 --> 00:31:51,487
- It sure does.
- It is Sergeant Hippo.

470
00:31:51,893 --> 00:31:53,326
In camouflage.

471
00:31:53,493 --> 00:31:55,848
I don't care if it takes
the rest of my life.

472
00:31:56,013 --> 00:31:59,722
- I'm gonna find out which of you...
- Has anyone seen Sergeant Hippo?

473
00:31:59,893 --> 00:32:01,565
Here, sir.

474
00:32:01,733 --> 00:32:04,531
What are you trying to do?
Put on a minstrel show?

475
00:32:04,693 --> 00:32:06,729
We've got an inspection
in 10 minutes.

476
00:32:06,893 --> 00:32:09,282
- Yes, sir.
- You're a fine example for the men.

477
00:32:09,453 --> 00:32:12,286
Get out and try to make yourself
look like a trooper.

478
00:32:12,453 --> 00:32:14,205
Yes, lieutenant.

479
00:32:14,373 --> 00:32:16,170
Carry on.

480
00:32:16,333 --> 00:32:17,971
Did you get a load of the big noise?

481
00:32:18,133 --> 00:32:19,168
[LAUGHING]

482
00:32:19,333 --> 00:32:21,847
His face is all black.
Old Black Joe.

483
00:32:22,013 --> 00:32:23,526
Yes.

484
00:32:23,693 --> 00:32:27,732
- I never saw...
- I didn't either.

485
00:32:30,893 --> 00:32:32,565
[BUGLE PLAYING]

486
00:32:36,813 --> 00:32:39,281
MAN:
Attention!

487
00:32:49,213 --> 00:32:50,692
Hey.

488
00:32:52,053 --> 00:32:53,691
Hi, buddies.

489
00:32:54,613 --> 00:32:57,252
Present arms!

490
00:33:13,413 --> 00:33:17,372
Of all the insolent, stubborn...
We're shipping her home tomorrow.

491
00:33:17,533 --> 00:33:19,205
She'll never stand the altitude.

492
00:33:19,373 --> 00:33:22,410
You get rid of that bird
before the Army gets rid of us.

493
00:33:22,573 --> 00:33:24,848
What am I going to do with her?

494
00:33:25,613 --> 00:33:29,242
Ditch her. Here comes the colonel,
the general, the whole outfit.

495
00:33:29,413 --> 00:33:31,165
- Hurry up!
- Quick! Hold this gun.

496
00:33:31,333 --> 00:33:34,530
All right, hurry up, now.
Get rid of it.

497
00:33:44,653 --> 00:33:47,042
What did you wanna put that
in my pants for?

498
00:33:47,213 --> 00:33:48,407
[BIRD CAWING]

499
00:33:54,733 --> 00:33:56,451
[GRUNTING]

500
00:34:04,253 --> 00:34:05,732
[BIRD CACKLES]

501
00:34:06,373 --> 00:34:08,443
- What was that?
- A frog in the throat...

502
00:34:08,613 --> 00:34:09,887
[COUGHING]

503
00:34:10,053 --> 00:34:11,042
...sir.

504
00:34:11,213 --> 00:34:13,169
Are you men with Troop D?

505
00:34:13,333 --> 00:34:15,289
Yes, sir, we're neighbors
of Troop C.

506
00:34:15,453 --> 00:34:17,444
They're the swellest bunch.

507
00:34:24,093 --> 00:34:25,321
Ah!

508
00:34:26,013 --> 00:34:27,924
Are you nervous, son?

509
00:34:28,093 --> 00:34:31,881
- A little, sir.
- He's the sensitive type.

510
00:34:34,053 --> 00:34:39,127
- Now, just relax, soldier.
- I'll try to, sir.

511
00:34:39,973 --> 00:34:42,203
As you were!

512
00:34:42,573 --> 00:34:44,848
- What is all this?
- We like him, sir.

513
00:34:45,013 --> 00:34:47,573
He's very nice to us.

514
00:34:55,733 --> 00:34:57,963
Turn that over!

515
00:34:58,573 --> 00:34:59,562
[CAWING]

516
00:34:59,733 --> 00:35:00,848
Oh!

517
00:35:05,173 --> 00:35:07,562
Ah! Ooh.

518
00:35:21,693 --> 00:35:23,729
OLLIE:
Ooh! Ooh!

519
00:35:38,453 --> 00:35:39,568
[BIRD CAWING]

520
00:35:39,733 --> 00:35:41,451
Was that a blackbird?

521
00:35:41,613 --> 00:35:45,572
No, sir. They don't come
this far south.

522
00:35:46,173 --> 00:35:48,926
Get that walleyed peacock
out of there!

523
00:35:49,093 --> 00:35:50,685
Yes, sir.

524
00:35:54,413 --> 00:35:56,643
[GRUNTING]

525
00:36:01,213 --> 00:36:05,445
Take Highway 66,
and when you get...

526
00:36:06,493 --> 00:36:09,565
You call this a military formation?

527
00:36:09,733 --> 00:36:13,726
I want a full report of this
sent to headquarters at once.

528
00:36:17,973 --> 00:36:20,123
Dismissed!

529
00:36:23,813 --> 00:36:28,091
OLLIE: I was never so humiliated
in all my life.

530
00:36:28,253 --> 00:36:31,609
Nothing to laugh at. I thought you
were pretty good.

531
00:36:31,773 --> 00:36:33,445
If I knew the Army
was so fun...

532
00:36:33,613 --> 00:36:36,889
...I'd have enlisted long ago.
- It's all in the point of view.

533
00:36:37,053 --> 00:36:39,851
STAN: Yes, sir.
- I'm gonna get our pictures. So long.

534
00:36:40,013 --> 00:36:42,811
- So long.
- Goodbye. I hope they turn out good.

535
00:36:42,973 --> 00:36:45,692
- I'm worried about that boy.
- What's the matter?

536
00:36:45,853 --> 00:36:48,162
He's been acting strange
the last day or two.

537
00:36:48,333 --> 00:36:50,563
- Strange?
- He's too happy.

538
00:36:50,733 --> 00:36:53,611
You know how he was
before he went into Watson's malady?

539
00:36:53,773 --> 00:36:55,331
I'll never forget it.

540
00:36:55,493 --> 00:36:56,846
That was terrible.

541
00:37:10,893 --> 00:37:11,882
- Say, Ollie.
- What?

542
00:37:12,053 --> 00:37:13,566
What time is it?

543
00:37:13,733 --> 00:37:16,964
- It's nearly half past.
- Thank you, Ollie.

544
00:37:30,293 --> 00:37:33,205
- Hello there, trooper.
DANIEL: Good evening.

545
00:37:37,173 --> 00:37:38,731
Hey, what's this?

546
00:37:38,893 --> 00:37:40,406
Did I win the daily double?

547
00:37:40,573 --> 00:37:43,531
That was a dollar bill you gave me.
I thought it was a 5.

548
00:37:43,693 --> 00:37:44,728
Even so, you counted 10.

549
00:37:44,893 --> 00:37:46,292
[SINGING]
<i>You'll never get rich...</i>

550
00:37:46,453 --> 00:37:48,603
I know the song. Anyway,
what's money?

551
00:37:48,773 --> 00:37:52,004
- Mere scraps of paper. I hate it.
- Me too.

552
00:37:52,173 --> 00:37:53,970
Come on, how about another nickel?

553
00:37:54,133 --> 00:37:56,363
Oh, dear. I must be slipping.

554
00:37:56,533 --> 00:37:58,125
- Good night, Ginger.
- Night.

555
00:37:58,293 --> 00:37:59,612
Are my pictures finished?

556
00:37:59,773 --> 00:38:01,331
You didn't give me your name.

557
00:38:01,493 --> 00:38:04,007
They're easily identified.
I'm in the pictures.

558
00:38:04,173 --> 00:38:06,129
Yes, now, let's see. I remember.

559
00:38:06,293 --> 00:38:09,012
You were standing
with an observation balloon and a...

560
00:38:09,173 --> 00:38:11,971
- A fire hydrant.
- That's the one with Oliver and Stan.

561
00:38:12,133 --> 00:38:13,885
They're in the darkroom.
Wanna see?

562
00:38:14,053 --> 00:38:16,772
- lf it's not too much trouble.
- Come on in.

563
00:38:17,533 --> 00:38:19,842
Here they are.

564
00:38:20,013 --> 00:38:23,289
- That's my first day at camp.
- Before they issued your muscles.

565
00:38:23,453 --> 00:38:25,842
- That's right.
- The Army agrees with you.

566
00:38:26,013 --> 00:38:28,004
I like it more all the time.

567
00:38:28,173 --> 00:38:30,323
I've heard that record played before.

568
00:38:30,493 --> 00:38:34,566
Maybe you have, but I find Army life
very fascinating.

569
00:38:35,213 --> 00:38:37,966
- I thought you meant...
- That's exactly what I meant.

570
00:38:38,133 --> 00:38:40,772
In spite of the hard work, I like it.

571
00:38:40,933 --> 00:38:42,810
Look, a double exposure.

572
00:38:42,973 --> 00:38:45,851
We've spoiled that one.
I'm on it twice.

573
00:38:46,013 --> 00:38:48,607
Well, I don't think that spoils it.

574
00:38:51,853 --> 00:38:56,131
That's me on a bucking horse.
Boy, I sure had my hands full.

575
00:38:56,293 --> 00:38:59,763
- Yes, isn't that a good action shot?
- Yeah.

576
00:39:04,653 --> 00:39:06,405
[BELL RINGS]

577
00:39:08,933 --> 00:39:10,730
- Hello, Hippo.
- Hi, Ginge.

578
00:39:10,893 --> 00:39:13,202
How about zooming
over to San Felipe tonight?

579
00:39:13,373 --> 00:39:15,284
- Zooming?
- I borrowed a motorcycle...

580
00:39:15,453 --> 00:39:17,762
...and took off the sidecar.
You'll ride on the tank.

581
00:39:17,933 --> 00:39:19,844
- On a motorcycle?
- Jump into slacks...

582
00:39:20,013 --> 00:39:22,243
...and let's get to whizzing.
- Not me, pal.

583
00:39:22,413 --> 00:39:26,122
- All right, we'll take the bus, then.
- Not tonight. Thanks, my boy.

584
00:39:26,293 --> 00:39:28,170
Listen, you can't do that to me.

585
00:39:28,333 --> 00:39:31,848
Millie wanted me to take her.
I said no, you and me had a date.

586
00:39:32,013 --> 00:39:34,811
Well, now, isn't that dandy?
Maybe I have a date.

587
00:39:34,973 --> 00:39:37,965
- Come on. Let's get going, will you?
- Sorry, Hippo.

588
00:39:38,133 --> 00:39:41,091
Listen, sugarfoot, little old Hips
has had a tough day...

589
00:39:41,253 --> 00:39:42,971
...and he sure could use
some giggling.

590
00:39:43,133 --> 00:39:44,725
[LAUGHING]

591
00:39:44,893 --> 00:39:47,885
Here's one of Sergeant Hippo
that'll make you laugh.

592
00:39:48,053 --> 00:39:49,884
Hello, sergeant. Did you see this?

593
00:39:50,373 --> 00:39:54,571
I ain't interested. Listen, Mr. Got-Rocks,
what did I say about that darkroom?

594
00:39:54,733 --> 00:39:57,201
- I looked up regulations...
- It's out of bounds.

595
00:39:57,373 --> 00:39:59,648
This happens to be
a private concession.

596
00:39:59,813 --> 00:40:02,373
- Yeah, so I noticed.
- Now, let's not have a row.

597
00:40:02,533 --> 00:40:05,093
There won't be any row
if Mr. Fancy-Pants here...

598
00:40:05,253 --> 00:40:07,608
...stays out of that darkroom.
- Excuse me.

599
00:40:07,773 --> 00:40:09,286
- With muscles!
- Wait a minute.

600
00:40:09,453 --> 00:40:11,967
Aren't you going to keep
your date with me?

601
00:40:12,133 --> 00:40:15,125
- What?
- You mean you got a date with him?

602
00:40:15,293 --> 00:40:18,569
Yes, I'm sorry. I made it just a moment
before you came in.

603
00:40:18,733 --> 00:40:21,770
How do you like that?
He ain't even a first-class private.

604
00:40:21,933 --> 00:40:24,811
I think he is. Even if he doesn't wear it
on his sleeve.

605
00:40:25,493 --> 00:40:27,484
Ginger, you murder me.

606
00:40:27,653 --> 00:40:30,963
Now, look, if you hurry,
you might catch Millie.

607
00:40:31,133 --> 00:40:34,170
I might, at that. Yeah!

608
00:40:35,053 --> 00:40:39,205
Hey, and that darkroom
is still out of bounds.

609
00:40:39,533 --> 00:40:42,570
- Now, that's a character.
- Yeah. He is different.

610
00:40:42,733 --> 00:40:45,850
I hope I wasn't too presumptuous,
telling him we had a date.

611
00:40:46,013 --> 00:40:47,969
That's all right. I don't mind.

612
00:40:48,133 --> 00:40:51,091
- Well, I'll see you tomorrow.
- Wait a minute, soldier.

613
00:40:51,253 --> 00:40:54,848
You're a peculiar duck. Are you married
or engaged or something?

614
00:40:55,013 --> 00:40:57,732
No, nothing like that. Why?

615
00:40:57,893 --> 00:41:00,487
- Were you just born frightened?
- I don't remember.

616
00:41:00,653 --> 00:41:04,089
They never let me get around much
before now.

617
00:41:04,253 --> 00:41:06,892
Say, how would you like to keep
that date with me?

618
00:41:07,853 --> 00:41:10,128
That'd be swell!

619
00:41:10,293 --> 00:41:13,649
Well, fine. I'll get my hat.

620
00:41:15,733 --> 00:41:18,770
Well, what do you know?

621
00:41:27,613 --> 00:41:29,331
Any sign of Daniel?

622
00:41:29,493 --> 00:41:32,166
The men haven't seen him.
Maybe he deserted.

623
00:41:32,333 --> 00:41:34,324
- Us?
- No, the Army.

624
00:41:34,493 --> 00:41:36,449
Now, what'll he do
without you and me?

625
00:41:36,613 --> 00:41:38,092
I shouldn't wonder.

626
00:41:38,613 --> 00:41:41,127
It's getting late. If he's not back
by next Thursday...

627
00:41:41,293 --> 00:41:43,443
...I'm going to notify
the War Department.

628
00:41:43,613 --> 00:41:45,729
That's a good idea.

629
00:43:10,133 --> 00:43:11,327
[DANIEL HUMMING]

630
00:43:11,493 --> 00:43:13,961
DANIEL: Good evening, boys.
- Daniel! Where've you been?

631
00:43:14,133 --> 00:43:17,250
We've been worrying about you.
Do you know it's after 8:00?

632
00:43:17,413 --> 00:43:19,608
I've been taking a lesson
in photography.

633
00:43:19,773 --> 00:43:22,241
Well, you seem unusually happy
about it.

634
00:43:22,413 --> 00:43:24,802
I am. It's a wonderful hobby.

635
00:43:24,973 --> 00:43:27,726
What's come over you?
You never sung before.

636
00:43:27,893 --> 00:43:30,532
Well, I never had anything
to sing about before.

637
00:43:30,693 --> 00:43:33,890
Is merely developing pictures
such a joy?

638
00:43:34,053 --> 00:43:36,726
More than I ever realized.

639
00:43:39,253 --> 00:43:40,686
That kid's got me worried.

640
00:43:40,853 --> 00:43:45,404
He certainly has changed.
Wouldn't know it was the same boy.

641
00:43:56,573 --> 00:44:00,009
Stanley, what time is it?

642
00:44:01,573 --> 00:44:03,962
It's about half past...

643
00:44:10,533 --> 00:44:14,082
Something went wrong.

644
00:44:16,413 --> 00:44:18,608
[BUGLE PLAYING]

645
00:44:21,853 --> 00:44:23,844
[SNORING]

646
00:44:30,533 --> 00:44:33,525
Some... Out of bounds...

647
00:44:33,693 --> 00:44:36,890
Out of bounds?
Not for me, it isn't.

648
00:44:37,053 --> 00:44:38,611
Not anymore.

649
00:44:39,173 --> 00:44:40,925
Can't see.

650
00:44:41,093 --> 00:44:43,368
Ginger! Ginger!

651
00:44:43,533 --> 00:44:47,208
Why, it's the darkroom,
and it isn't out of bounds for me.

652
00:44:47,813 --> 00:44:49,644
- Is it, Gin...?
- Somnambulism.

653
00:44:49,813 --> 00:44:52,202
- Some talk.
- I knew that Daniel would never...

654
00:44:52,373 --> 00:44:54,284
...withstand the rigors of Army life.

655
00:44:54,453 --> 00:44:56,330
Think we should phone Dr. Schickel?

656
00:44:56,493 --> 00:44:58,643
- I love you, Ginger.
- Hear that?

657
00:44:58,813 --> 00:45:01,964
He loves ginger.
Never could eat it at home.

658
00:45:02,133 --> 00:45:04,124
You'll love Agatha and Martha...

659
00:45:04,293 --> 00:45:08,172
- Now I know he's dreaming.
- Do you think Ginger could be a woman?

660
00:45:08,333 --> 00:45:09,766
Could be a cookie.

661
00:45:09,933 --> 00:45:14,085
The darkroom. A beautiful darkroom.

662
00:45:14,253 --> 00:45:16,209
Just let me look at you, Ginger.

663
00:45:16,373 --> 00:45:19,251
- It is a cookie!
- He's in love.

664
00:45:19,413 --> 00:45:22,086
STAN: His heart will never stand it.
- Daniel, Daniel!

665
00:45:22,253 --> 00:45:24,562
- You're too late, sergeant.
- It's me, Oliver.

666
00:45:24,733 --> 00:45:28,248
- What's the matter?
- Who's Ginger?

667
00:45:28,413 --> 00:45:31,564
She's the most wonderful girl
in the world.

668
00:45:31,733 --> 00:45:34,042
Take one of these.
It'll make you forget her.

669
00:45:34,213 --> 00:45:35,487
I don't wanna forget her.

670
00:45:35,653 --> 00:45:38,213
Remember what Dr. Schickel said
about your heart.

671
00:45:38,373 --> 00:45:42,048
- A romance would be fatal.
- Please, boys.

672
00:45:42,213 --> 00:45:45,171
Go back to sleep
and let me dream.

673
00:45:45,333 --> 00:45:48,291
All right. But don't overdo it.

674
00:45:50,733 --> 00:45:52,086
[BIRD CAWING]

675
00:46:01,853 --> 00:46:03,923
[BIRD CAWING]

676
00:46:25,653 --> 00:46:28,611
You may wait for us, my good man.

677
00:46:28,773 --> 00:46:31,412
I hope it won't take long.
You know, after 4:00...

678
00:46:31,573 --> 00:46:34,451
...we pay overtime for these outfits.

679
00:46:34,613 --> 00:46:38,128
She'll be putty in my hands.

680
00:46:45,253 --> 00:46:47,528
Virginia Hammond. Virginia Hammond.

681
00:46:47,693 --> 00:46:49,968
MAN:
Miss Hammond lives upstairs in 204.

682
00:46:50,133 --> 00:46:52,124
Thank you very much.

683
00:46:56,493 --> 00:46:58,643
That's right. Second floor.

684
00:46:58,813 --> 00:47:01,771
Thank you very much.

685
00:47:12,173 --> 00:47:14,129
Remember what
you're supposed to be?

686
00:47:14,293 --> 00:47:18,002
- Sure. I'm a typhoon.
- Not typhoon, tycoon.

687
00:47:18,173 --> 00:47:20,323
A Wall Street tycoon.

688
00:47:20,493 --> 00:47:24,281
- With a stock on the Seat Exchange.
- That's right...

689
00:47:24,453 --> 00:47:28,526
Just forget it. I'll do the talking.
Stock on the Seat Ex...

690
00:47:28,733 --> 00:47:29,961
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

691
00:47:37,773 --> 00:47:39,172
How do you do?

692
00:47:39,333 --> 00:47:40,812
- Miss Hammond?
- Yes.

693
00:47:40,973 --> 00:47:45,364
My name is Murgatroy. This is my
business colleague, Mr. Sylvester Sneer.

694
00:47:45,533 --> 00:47:49,287
We're here on a very important mission.

695
00:47:49,453 --> 00:47:51,648
- Well, won't you come in?
- Thank you.

696
00:47:51,813 --> 00:47:55,123
Come, Silly.
I call him Silly for short.

697
00:47:56,573 --> 00:47:59,770
- Sit down, gentlemen.
- Thank you.

698
00:48:05,653 --> 00:48:09,532
Nice, cozy little nest you have here,
Miss Hammond.

699
00:48:09,693 --> 00:48:11,206
Well, it's comfortable.

700
00:48:11,373 --> 00:48:14,570
If you don't think so, you ought to sleep
in an Army tent.

701
00:48:14,733 --> 00:48:16,724
We slept in one last night.

702
00:48:16,893 --> 00:48:21,011
Quite an experience. We're inspecting
Fort Merritt for the government.

703
00:48:21,173 --> 00:48:22,447
Dollar-a-year men.

704
00:48:22,613 --> 00:48:26,003
You'd be surprised how little
we can save out of that.

705
00:48:27,173 --> 00:48:28,367
[OLLIE CLEARS THROAT]

706
00:48:29,253 --> 00:48:31,483
Now, look. What's this
all about, gentlemen?

707
00:48:31,653 --> 00:48:34,326
Well, it's all about...

708
00:48:34,493 --> 00:48:36,723
It's all about Daniel Forrester.

709
00:48:36,893 --> 00:48:39,930
OLLIE: You know him, of course.
- Why, I certainly do.

710
00:48:40,093 --> 00:48:41,651
I think he's a wonderful boy.

711
00:48:41,813 --> 00:48:47,012
- But as poor as a church mouse.
- And sick as a dog.

712
00:48:47,413 --> 00:48:50,405
- I don't understand.
- Neither does he.

713
00:48:50,573 --> 00:48:54,327
Poor boy, he thinks he's wealthy,
but, Miss Hammond...

714
00:48:54,493 --> 00:48:58,884
...Daniel Forrester is bankrupt.
- Absolutely broke.

715
00:48:59,053 --> 00:49:01,851
Our firm has been financing him
for years.

716
00:49:02,013 --> 00:49:04,811
But only because of
his hopeless physical condition...

717
00:49:04,973 --> 00:49:07,931
...has his hopeless financial condition
been kept secret.

718
00:49:08,093 --> 00:49:10,812
Mr. Sneer and I have been carrying
quite a burden.

719
00:49:10,973 --> 00:49:15,728
Believe me, my dear,
it has cost us a king's ransom.

720
00:49:16,173 --> 00:49:18,403
Thank you.

721
00:49:21,173 --> 00:49:23,926
But what has all this
to do with me?

722
00:49:24,093 --> 00:49:26,926
Well, to take the bull by the horns...

723
00:49:27,093 --> 00:49:31,166
...Daniel could never support you
on his meager salary.

724
00:49:31,333 --> 00:49:34,609
And they take out for laundry too.
We know.

725
00:49:34,773 --> 00:49:36,331
Daniel!

726
00:49:36,493 --> 00:49:39,929
My Daniel! Broke!

727
00:49:40,133 --> 00:49:42,010
[MOANS]

728
00:49:42,173 --> 00:49:43,925
Flatter than a sand dab.

729
00:49:46,493 --> 00:49:48,927
Did he send you here?

730
00:49:49,093 --> 00:49:51,448
No. Daniel's too proud.

731
00:49:51,613 --> 00:49:55,811
- The poor, deluded darling.
- I knew you would understand.

732
00:49:55,973 --> 00:49:59,648
- Understand? Understand what?
- Why, that you'd give him up.

733
00:49:59,813 --> 00:50:03,249
Give up Daniel? The only thing
I have left? Are you mad?

734
00:50:03,413 --> 00:50:05,404
No. Just practical.

735
00:50:05,573 --> 00:50:08,133
What have I done to deserve this?

736
00:50:08,293 --> 00:50:11,922
All my life I've hoped and prayed
for a Prince Charming...

737
00:50:12,093 --> 00:50:16,405
...that would ride up on his white steed
and sweep me into his heart.

738
00:50:16,573 --> 00:50:19,690
And now to have it all vanish,
like a shattered dream.

739
00:50:19,853 --> 00:50:21,923
But you'll have your youth,
your charm...

740
00:50:22,093 --> 00:50:25,210
- You're beautiful.
- Give up this human derelict.

741
00:50:25,373 --> 00:50:26,692
No!

742
00:50:26,853 --> 00:50:31,290
Without Daniel, I'm nothing.
A mere empty shell.

743
00:50:31,893 --> 00:50:34,123
All right, Miss Hammond.

744
00:50:34,293 --> 00:50:36,887
What is your price
to release your prisoner?

745
00:50:37,053 --> 00:50:40,204
Now, don't forget:
we're only dollar-a-year men.

746
00:50:41,493 --> 00:50:43,211
You offer me money?

747
00:50:43,373 --> 00:50:47,924
Come, come, my dear.
Daniel is not such a bargain.

748
00:50:48,093 --> 00:50:52,166
Please, please. I'm confused.

749
00:50:52,333 --> 00:50:56,121
Miss Hammond,
I am awaiting your answer.

750
00:50:59,333 --> 00:51:03,531
- No, no, Mr...
- Purgatory...

751
00:51:03,693 --> 00:51:05,285
- Murgatroy.
- Murgatroy.

752
00:51:05,453 --> 00:51:08,843
All of your wealth isn't enough
for me to make this sacrifice.

753
00:51:09,013 --> 00:51:12,688
See? I told you we were short.
Start it at a dollar and a half.

754
00:51:12,853 --> 00:51:14,127
Get out!

755
00:51:14,293 --> 00:51:16,602
- Get out!
- But wait. Wait.

756
00:51:16,773 --> 00:51:19,241
- Get out.
- You're taking an innocent man's life.

757
00:51:19,413 --> 00:51:21,449
Get out!

758
00:51:26,733 --> 00:51:28,086
Get out!

759
00:51:28,253 --> 00:51:31,643
Get out, you stu...
You charlatan, you!

760
00:51:33,853 --> 00:51:37,323
- What's a charlatan?
- Get out.

761
00:51:37,493 --> 00:51:40,132
Boy, she's a tough customer.

762
00:51:40,293 --> 00:51:42,363
What are you moping about?

763
00:51:42,533 --> 00:51:45,172
She's so sweet.

764
00:51:47,493 --> 00:51:49,324
Come on.

765
00:51:50,053 --> 00:51:52,851
She's a woman to be reckoned with,
all right.

766
00:51:53,013 --> 00:51:55,129
Personally, I thought she
was very nice.

767
00:51:55,293 --> 00:51:58,603
Now, what do you know about women
of the world?

768
00:51:58,773 --> 00:52:00,570
DANIEL: Hello, boys.
OLLIE: Hello, Daniel.

769
00:52:00,733 --> 00:52:03,293
STAN: Hello, Daniel.
- Say, we got a surprise for you.

770
00:52:03,453 --> 00:52:05,808
DANIEL: Really?
- We're treating you to a movie.

771
00:52:05,973 --> 00:52:10,251
- And you can stay up till 10:00.
- 12:30. It's a double feature.

772
00:52:10,413 --> 00:52:13,211
Yeah. And they're showing
a Mickey Duck.

773
00:52:13,373 --> 00:52:16,126
Thanks a lot, boys.
But I have a date with Ginger.

774
00:52:18,653 --> 00:52:22,692
Daniel, you shouldn't go out
with girls. It's dangerous.

775
00:52:22,853 --> 00:52:24,684
It might affect your heart.

776
00:52:24,853 --> 00:52:28,243
It has already. For the first time,
it's starting to beat.

777
00:52:32,293 --> 00:52:33,885
[GONGING NOISE]

778
00:52:39,373 --> 00:52:42,331
- What?
- Our last hope is in Sergeant Hippo.

779
00:52:42,493 --> 00:52:44,882
- We'll ask his advice.
- He'll charge us for it.

780
00:52:45,053 --> 00:52:47,248
- It's worth it. Come on.
- Where you going?

781
00:52:47,413 --> 00:52:50,564
I'm going over and see Ser...
Come on. Get up...

782
00:52:54,613 --> 00:52:56,012
HIPPO:
Well?

783
00:53:01,653 --> 00:53:03,609
Come in!

784
00:53:03,973 --> 00:53:05,850
Stanley.

785
00:53:13,773 --> 00:53:16,241
I thought you went out of town
for the weekend.

786
00:53:16,413 --> 00:53:18,324
No, sir. We like it here.

787
00:53:18,493 --> 00:53:20,484
Sergeant, we need some advice.

788
00:53:20,653 --> 00:53:23,042
That's what I'm here for.
What's on your mind?

789
00:53:23,213 --> 00:53:25,044
Daniel's going to kill himself.

790
00:53:25,213 --> 00:53:28,762
- Oh, is that all.
- He's infatuated with a woman.

791
00:53:28,933 --> 00:53:31,766
- Yeah? Who is it?
- Vanilla or lemon. Or some...

792
00:53:31,933 --> 00:53:33,082
- Ginger!
- Oh, Ginger.

793
00:53:33,253 --> 00:53:35,130
- Ginger Hammond?
- Then you know her.

794
00:53:35,293 --> 00:53:38,251
- You see, she's notorious.
- It'll mean the end of Daniel.

795
00:53:38,413 --> 00:53:40,643
- I'll say it will.
- I knew you'd understand.

796
00:53:40,813 --> 00:53:43,281
- You better hurry before it's too late.
- Yeah...

797
00:53:43,453 --> 00:53:45,762
...he's meeting her tonight.
Maybe a talk...

798
00:53:45,933 --> 00:53:49,926
...will convince him of his folly.
- That's a cinch.

799
00:53:50,733 --> 00:53:52,166
- You know what, Ollie?
- What?

800
00:53:52,333 --> 00:53:55,370
Deep down in his heart,
that sergeant's a good kid.

801
00:53:55,533 --> 00:54:00,482
- A prince among men.
HIPPO: Come on, you yaps!

802
00:54:02,773 --> 00:54:04,650
[HUMMING]

803
00:54:06,893 --> 00:54:09,327
- Hello.
- Where do you think you're going?

804
00:54:09,493 --> 00:54:11,165
Into town. It's Saturday.

805
00:54:11,333 --> 00:54:14,086
- Think you're gonna see Ginger?
- How'd you guess it?

806
00:54:14,253 --> 00:54:17,290
HIPPO: If you know what's good for you,
you'll stay away from her.

807
00:54:17,893 --> 00:54:19,963
DANIEL: Sorry.
She's expecting me tonight.

808
00:54:20,133 --> 00:54:21,930
And I wouldn't disappoint the lady.

809
00:54:22,093 --> 00:54:24,209
HIPPO:
If you're smart, you will.

810
00:54:24,613 --> 00:54:25,841
[OLLIE YELPS]

811
00:54:26,053 --> 00:54:27,122
Shh!

812
00:54:36,653 --> 00:54:40,328
Hello, sergeant, long time no see.

813
00:54:40,653 --> 00:54:43,042
Your friend here's a pretty brave guy.

814
00:54:43,213 --> 00:54:47,001
All right, sergeant. Have you
anything more to say?

815
00:54:47,173 --> 00:54:50,961
- Just that I warned you.
- I'll take the chance.

816
00:54:53,293 --> 00:54:55,523
Listen, Diamond Jim,
that's insubordination.

817
00:54:55,693 --> 00:54:57,524
I could be plenty tough on you.

818
00:54:58,053 --> 00:55:00,521
But I'm gonna be fair.

819
00:55:05,453 --> 00:55:07,842
All right, your furlough is over,
wise guy.

820
00:55:08,013 --> 00:55:10,049
It's the guardhouse for you.
Come on.

821
00:55:10,213 --> 00:55:12,852
- Fellas!
- Come on!

822
00:55:14,173 --> 00:55:17,927
- Haven't you anything to say?
- I ain't interested. Come on. Get going.

823
00:55:27,653 --> 00:55:30,326
- You know what, Ollie?
- What?

824
00:55:30,493 --> 00:55:32,848
I feel like a mouse.

825
00:55:33,013 --> 00:55:37,245
We had to do it.
It hurt me more than it did him.

826
00:55:37,413 --> 00:55:39,722
Poor Daniel!

827
00:55:41,613 --> 00:55:43,490
[CRYING]

828
00:55:54,093 --> 00:55:56,163
MAN:
Well, there goes our trip, Chuck.

829
00:55:56,333 --> 00:55:58,403
Here's where we hit the saddle,
but hard.

830
00:55:58,573 --> 00:56:01,804
- I wonder what problems they'll give us.
- You got me.

831
00:56:02,493 --> 00:56:06,725
The military problem in this maneuver
will include our entire fighting force.

832
00:56:06,893 --> 00:56:10,932
The division will be divided
into two opposing combat units:

833
00:56:11,093 --> 00:56:13,812
The Blue Force and the White Force.

834
00:56:13,973 --> 00:56:18,285
Now, the Blue Force, with a battalion
of engineers attached...

835
00:56:18,453 --> 00:56:22,048
...will attack the Whites from an area
along the 70 miles of river...

836
00:56:22,213 --> 00:56:23,566
...designated here.

837
00:56:23,733 --> 00:56:26,042
However, before they attack...

838
00:56:26,213 --> 00:56:28,852
...they will construct
a pontoon bridge...

839
00:56:29,013 --> 00:56:31,811
...over which the brigade
must pass before invading...

840
00:56:31,973 --> 00:56:33,804
...the area occupied by the Whites.

841
00:56:33,973 --> 00:56:37,648
The problem of the White Force
is to detect the secret location...

842
00:56:37,813 --> 00:56:40,885
...of this bridgehead and destroy it
before it's completed.

843
00:56:41,093 --> 00:56:43,004
[BUGLE PLAYING]

844
00:56:46,853 --> 00:56:50,289
OLLIE:
Hey, Daniel. Come here.

845
00:56:51,773 --> 00:56:54,207
Hello, Daniel. We've come
to say goodbye.

846
00:56:54,373 --> 00:56:55,692
Well, goodbye.

847
00:56:55,853 --> 00:56:59,607
We're sorry for what happened,
but we had to save you from yourself.

848
00:56:59,773 --> 00:57:03,163
- Yeah. She was a real vampire.
- Forget it.

849
00:57:03,333 --> 00:57:07,292
- We're gonna play soldier.
- They put us in the White Army.

850
00:57:07,453 --> 00:57:09,250
We're fighting the Blue Bloods.

851
00:57:09,413 --> 00:57:13,770
And we bet Sergeant Hippo
$40 to his 20 that we win.

852
00:57:13,933 --> 00:57:16,447
- He's giving us 2-1.
- Yeah.

853
00:57:16,613 --> 00:57:18,285
[BUGLE PLAYING]

854
00:57:18,453 --> 00:57:21,365
Goodbye, Daniel.
Remember your diet, now.

855
00:57:21,533 --> 00:57:23,763
- See you after the war. Goodbye.
- Goodbye.

856
00:57:23,933 --> 00:57:25,924
Goodbye, Daniel.

857
00:57:31,213 --> 00:57:32,646
MAN: B-2 Patrol!
- Yes, sir.

858
00:57:32,813 --> 00:57:34,644
Follow this terrain to the river.

859
00:57:34,813 --> 00:57:36,451
Yes, sir.

860
00:57:41,813 --> 00:57:43,371
[ENGINE RUMBLES]

861
00:57:55,613 --> 00:57:58,002
- Is this part of the river being scouted?
- Yes.

862
00:57:58,173 --> 00:58:01,131
Colonel Wayburn's Blue Army
might build a bridge there.

863
00:58:01,293 --> 00:58:03,853
I have a party reconnoitering
in that sector now.

864
00:58:04,013 --> 00:58:05,002
Good.

865
00:58:17,653 --> 00:58:19,803
[OLLIE GASPING AND GROANING]

866
00:58:54,253 --> 00:58:57,165
Can't you miss any of those things?

867
00:59:15,213 --> 00:59:16,282
[WHISTLES]

868
00:59:44,493 --> 00:59:46,768
OLLIE:
We're in a minefield. Step on it!

869
00:59:55,853 --> 00:59:59,050
B Patrol reporting from Sector 7.
No contact yet with enemy.

870
00:59:59,213 --> 01:00:01,647
- Proceed to Gila Point.
- Proceed to Gila Point.

871
01:00:01,813 --> 01:00:04,452
Yes, sir.
Proceed to Gila Point.

872
01:00:13,973 --> 01:00:15,292
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

873
01:00:15,893 --> 01:00:17,849
White Force scouting party?

874
01:00:18,013 --> 01:00:20,322
What are you waiting for?
Let them have it.

875
01:00:33,453 --> 01:00:34,806
[LAUGHING]

876
01:00:34,973 --> 01:00:37,567
Those Blue Boys couldn't hit
this side of a barn.

877
01:00:37,733 --> 01:00:39,610
You said it.

878
01:00:41,733 --> 01:00:44,611
You look like a biscuit.

879
01:01:03,893 --> 01:01:05,565
Well, we've found the river.

880
01:01:05,733 --> 01:01:07,007
How charming.

881
01:01:07,173 --> 01:01:11,610
Now, if we could only find the Blue Army
bridge, we'd get a medal just as sure as...

882
01:01:11,773 --> 01:01:13,092
MAN:
Hey, you!

883
01:01:13,253 --> 01:01:15,483
- You White Army men?
- Yes, sir.

884
01:01:15,653 --> 01:01:19,123
- Patrol B-2.
- And who are you, may we ask?

885
01:01:19,293 --> 01:01:21,932
This is Blue Army,
and you're our prisoners.

886
01:01:22,093 --> 01:01:25,563
Pleased to meet...
Oh.

887
01:01:25,733 --> 01:01:28,167
All right, come on.
Pile out of there.

888
01:01:28,573 --> 01:01:33,442
- What will we do?
- Lock the car so they can't use it.

889
01:01:36,613 --> 01:01:39,366
I'll put it in my mouth
in case they search me.

890
01:01:39,533 --> 01:01:42,127
That's a good idea, Ollie.

891
01:01:43,733 --> 01:01:47,203
Come on, you fellas.
Pile out of there.

892
01:01:53,013 --> 01:01:55,652
- White Army prisoners, sir. Patrol B-2.
- Confirmed.

893
01:01:55,813 --> 01:01:58,930
Report this to headquarters.
Put them to work on the bridge.

894
01:01:59,093 --> 01:02:01,163
- Yes, sir.
- That isn't exactly cricket.

895
01:02:01,333 --> 01:02:03,005
On the double, you guys.
Come on.

896
01:02:03,173 --> 01:02:04,845
Goodbye.

897
01:02:06,973 --> 01:02:10,249
Reporting capture
of your B-2 scouting party, sir.

898
01:02:11,213 --> 01:02:13,283
The stupid, blundering idiots!

899
01:02:17,013 --> 01:02:20,608
HIPPO: How does it feel to be
a yardbird in a gilded cage, soldier?

900
01:02:20,773 --> 01:02:24,209
You might be interested to know
your two buddies were captured.

901
01:02:24,373 --> 01:02:26,682
- Just got it through the grapevine.
- So what?

902
01:02:26,853 --> 01:02:29,765
So the Blues cross the bridge,
polish off the Whites...

903
01:02:29,933 --> 01:02:31,366
...and I'm 40 bucks ahead.

904
01:02:31,533 --> 01:02:33,763
- Just like that, huh?
- Yeah.

905
01:02:34,173 --> 01:02:36,323
Did you say Stan and Oliver
were captured?

906
01:02:36,493 --> 01:02:38,723
You heard me, and if I know
my maneuvers...

907
01:02:38,893 --> 01:02:42,169
...they're helping those engineers
build that bridge right now.

908
01:02:42,333 --> 01:02:44,244
They're a couple of pigeons.

909
01:02:44,413 --> 01:02:46,768
- But you haven't won yet.
- No.

910
01:02:46,933 --> 01:02:49,731
But I still got 50
that says the Blue Army wins.

911
01:02:54,533 --> 01:02:57,206
- I'll take that bet, sergeant.
- You're on, chump.

912
01:03:03,613 --> 01:03:08,004
Hey, where's that prisoner? He's gone.
SOLDIER: Hey!

913
01:03:29,373 --> 01:03:30,647
[BIRD CAWING]

914
01:03:40,773 --> 01:03:44,652
All right, guard, you take it
through there. Come on, you follow me.

915
01:03:47,773 --> 01:03:50,571
Penelope, here's your chance
to make good. Go to Stan.

916
01:03:50,733 --> 01:03:54,248
Stan, do you hear?
He's got a nice, fat worm for you.

917
01:04:00,013 --> 01:04:02,163
There he is!

918
01:04:05,013 --> 01:04:07,208
Hey!

919
01:04:41,053 --> 01:04:43,806
You'll get 20 years for this,
you deserter!

920
01:04:58,253 --> 01:05:01,370
Hey, don't work any harder
than you have to for these Blues.

921
01:05:01,533 --> 01:05:03,285
I won't.

922
01:05:05,493 --> 01:05:07,085
[STAN WHISTLING]

923
01:05:14,453 --> 01:05:17,013
- How's this?
- Perfect.

924
01:05:21,613 --> 01:05:24,650
The location of the Blue Army bridge
is still undetermined.

925
01:05:24,813 --> 01:05:28,522
If we don't find the bridge,
the Blue Army will cross and outflank us.

926
01:05:28,693 --> 01:05:31,332
But we haven't heard
from B-5 yet, sir.

927
01:05:34,173 --> 01:05:36,323
Sorry to interrupt.
I can find the bridge.

928
01:05:36,493 --> 01:05:39,371
- With what, a Ouija board?
- No, by following that bird.

929
01:05:39,533 --> 01:05:41,330
That bird?

930
01:05:41,973 --> 01:05:43,725
You remember. It's my buddy's pet.

931
01:05:43,893 --> 01:05:46,361
They're captured.
She's heading for the bridge.

932
01:05:46,533 --> 01:05:47,886
Report back to your troop!

933
01:05:48,053 --> 01:05:50,203
Hold on there, soldier.

934
01:05:50,893 --> 01:05:53,646
It's a long chance.
But we can't win...

935
01:05:53,813 --> 01:05:57,249
...waiting to be outmaneuvered.
Order the unit to follow this man!

936
01:05:57,413 --> 01:06:00,325
Yes, sir.
Attention, all troops!

937
01:06:17,213 --> 01:06:19,329
[WHISTLING]

938
01:06:54,613 --> 01:06:56,922
- The enemy's heading this way.
- How is the bridge?

939
01:06:57,093 --> 01:06:59,163
- Almost complete, sir.
- Deploy for counterattack.

940
01:06:59,333 --> 01:07:00,652
Deploy for counterattack.

941
01:07:00,813 --> 01:07:03,725
Command Post 4, Command Post 4.
Deploy for counterattack!

942
01:07:31,173 --> 01:07:32,526
[GUNS FIRING]

943
01:07:58,853 --> 01:07:59,922
[WHISTLING]

944
01:08:40,413 --> 01:08:44,770
Isn't there any place we can go
without that black pelican popping up?

945
01:08:44,933 --> 01:08:48,608
Penelope, did you know that your
Uncle Ollie and me have been captured?

946
01:08:48,773 --> 01:08:51,003
This is no place for pets.
Get back to work!

947
01:08:53,893 --> 01:08:56,885
Holy Hannah, it's the White Force!

948
01:08:58,213 --> 01:09:01,125
Well, that was the bridge, men.
The White Force wins.

949
01:09:01,293 --> 01:09:05,127
- We've won the war!
- Yeah, and our 40 bucks!

950
01:09:05,853 --> 01:09:06,922
